{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3d1dd7a-74fe-41a7-becb-83dc972bbc28","content":"This repo doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`. On macOS, use the **system crash reporter** instead:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** if you need a full memory dump:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears at `/tmp/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Use `lldb`** to inspect the core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, on dev machines you may need to partially disable System Integrity Protection, or run the app under `lldb` directly:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   run\n   # after crash:\n   bt        # backtrace\n   ```\n\n5. **Symbolicate Apple crash logs** using `atos`:\n   ```bash\n   atos -o /path/to/your/app -l <load_address> <crash_address>\n   ```\n\nThe Apple `.ips`/`.crash` reports (step 1) are usually the quickest path since they're collected automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5f7e316c-e10b-4dc2-a0cb-de2349311cb9","outputTokens":384,"requestId":"A0C3:2FD5E:68C8D:7C792:6A013700"},"id":"7fee0ec0-8542-4206-a565-f596b7306f36","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:55:22.592Z","parentId":"12e9b94a-8ff7-4ed1-85d9-2fb11189d2a7"}
